## What each new concept actually looks like here

- **Chunking** (`src/utils/chunking.py`): word-count-based splitter with
  configurable `chunk_size`/`overlap`. Run `python src/utils/chunking.py`
  directly for a standalone demo -- no other setup needed, since it doesn't
  touch Ollama or Chroma.
- **Metadata / section-wise categorization**: every chunk stored carries
  `{section, story_id, source, chunk_index}`. `check_retrieval.py --section
  projects` and `search_portfolio(section="projects")` both filter on it.
- **Retrieval checkup**: `check_retrieval.py` -- read the comments at the
  top of the file, they explain what the distance numbers mean and how to
  build intuition for "is this actually a good match."
- **RAG eval**: `rag_eval.py` -- deliberately scoped to retrieval quality
  (Hit@k), not generation quality, with comments on how to grow it into a
  generation-level eval later using the same rubric style you built at
  EPAM (quality, hallucination, bias, safety, consistency) -- that's the
  legitimate bridge between this demo and "I've done similar RAG eval
  work before."

## For the Infosys interview

This project now demonstrates, concretely and defensibly:
- **RAG**: real embeddings, real vector DB, chunking with a stated
  rationale, metadata-filtered retrieval, and a retrieval-quality eval --
  not just "I called an embed function once."
- **MCP Engineering**: 12 tools wrapping a real workflow, not a toy
  echo-tool -- including tools that trigger regeneration and reindexing,
  which is closer to "streamline developer workflows" than a single
  static Q&A tool would be.
- **Context engineering**: the static/dynamic memory split in
  `src/workflow.py`, plus retrieved context feeding `analyze_story` -- you
  can point at the exact `PROMPT_FIELDS` dict and explain why each prompt
  gets exactly the fields it needs, no more.

Be ready to say out loud, unprompted, the two design decisions that came
up while building this: (1) seeding is a separate script from the
workflow, not baked into `main()`, because seeding is a data-maintenance
concern and the workflow is a per-request concern; (2) `add_story_to_db`
upserts by id, so re-running seeding is always safe. Small details like
that are exactly what separates "followed a tutorial" from "understands
why the code is shaped this way" in an interview.
